Hello and welcome to the first installation of our new program.

In this chapter we will be exploring new and exciting ways to be more comfortable in a variety of social situations.

Chapter one: how to leave the apartment, how to avoid awkward silences, how to seem more interesting, how to impress literally anyone, how to land every joke, how to dress, how to find your opening, how to appear to be more intelligent, how to look and feel your best, how to be yourself and most importantly:


How to work a room.
Ah this stupid VCR player has been stuck on loop forever! Where did I put the remote?!?
Where is the remote?
Under the couch
On the bed
Matt checks under the couch, the remote isn't there. The overstimulation of the repeating, stuck VCR, makes him throw the whole thing across the room
Matt checks on the bed, the remote is there but a sense of hopelessness suddendly washes over him, thinking about the party he just attended, making him wanting to lie down for a bit.

Matt has been having more fits of range since being diagnosed with autism. It's like, suddendly he lost his ability to mask his emotions, reactions and behaviours.
The party he attended tonight didn't help and only reminded him how much people treat him differently.
Continue to self-loath?
Yes, sounds easy
Yes, to the point of death
Matt checks on the bed, the remote is there, the heavyness of his action catches up to him, thinking about the broken VCR and the party they just attended, making him wanting to lie down for a bit.
What do you wanna think about?
The party
Kimberly
Your diagnosis

Why would they tell me to bring my bags of bones? Just to make fun of me?? Why are people so cruel? Is it because I'm different? But they don't know I am. Have I been accidentally unmasking? What is wrong with me? How can I have a normal conversation? How can I appear more confident? Please world give me a sign.

Matt had just left the party which was supposed to be his moment, his occasion to "start again". Be the person he once was: profound, empathetic, extroverted and most importantly able to mingle with a room full of strangers. But as of now he just felt an empty shell of a person: predictable, didn't get any social clues, introverted and terrorized by strangers. Between himself he was thinking for the first time, that this person he had been chasing was actually fake, and his real "self" was actually this new version, emerging from the darkness, brought forth by a diagnosis, black on white paper, determined by a series of box checkmark tests.

*singing*


"It’s you"
"It’s only you, only you" "It's only you, only you, you"
"It’s only you, only you"
"It's only you, only you"

"And if you love again, don't expect something
new"
"It's you"
"It’s only you, only"


"And if you love again, don't expect something new"
"It's you"
"It's only you, only..."

When Matt was younger his mom used to bring him every weekend to Farrington's Pond to see the ducks, play with other children and most importantly get him to breathe some fresh air.
Matt had always been an "antisocial" child, as his mom liked to call him, "special", "old-soul" and "day dreamer" were other adjectives that were often thrown around.
Matt didn't really mind as long as he had his routine thirty minutes, once a week, time to look at ducks.
Everytime Matt went to the pond, it was like his little paradise, away from yesterday's apprehensions and the nightmares that controlled him.
Mom I had another nightmare, you know the ones I always get about ending up lonely forever?

Oh sweetheart you know you'll never be...

*singing*
"...lonely, lonely... you'll never be lonely..."

After the soul changing experience of his diagnosis, Matt kept thinking about a pond where he used to go when he was a child. But he ended up being confined by the strangest sensation, not being able to get out of bed for days.

He only managed to take a picture once or twice of his surroundings, posting it in his stories with some obscure retro reference or a song of an artist nobody cares about.
Matt knew that, but it made him feel connected in
a way, so he kept going, and going.
That was the extent of his activity for the first
week or so.
He decided to stop when he kept hearing phantom vibrations coming from his phone.

Everyone knew what had happened to him, but nobody bother to reach out to him for weeks.

Suddenly Matt was reminded that friendships tend to work both ways, and he tried reaching out to someone.


He was invited to an Halloween party, which made him jump from the bed, go brush his teeth and take a shower for the first time in weeks, all before he could even reply with:
"Yeah of course I'll be there"

Matt also recevied some weird instructions about what to bring to the party, but didn't think much of it as it was supposed to be an Halloween party, which obviously meant that it was supposed to be weird... right?
To initiate conversation: stay calm, stay connected, take a deep breath and upon exhalation simple say something that sounds...Profound.
Matt had tried to get the VCR started again. Although it wasn't broken - miraculously - it continued to loop in certain points and there was no apparent way to fix it

I could have really used this advice today...

If I followed this instruction, could I become an active, contributing and useful member of society?

I'm certainly not calm, nor the best at staying connected.


Also, I breath weird. I think. I don't know how normal people just... don't think about breathing.


Maybe that's part of the problem.


I should stop thinking about this...
I WON'T SPIRAL AGAIN!
Matt suddenly jumped and screamed. And then feel on the floor, creating a "thump" sound that made their downstairs neighbor, first startle, then pick up a broom and give a whack on the ceiling.
Matt didn't really care as he was now crying profusely, still on the floor.

*texting*
"Hey Matt, heard you're coming to the party, can't wait to see you xoxo"

Matt was taken aback for a second, receving such a message from someone he likes was quite unusual for him.
Even thought he considered himself aromantic, Matt was obsessed with Kimberly, in a way that went way past romantic or sexual attraction.

Matt go out of the house and walked to the party, as it was quite close from his flat.

Finally arriving, Kimberly was the one to open the door.
Heyy Matt, welcome! Come on in!

Kimberly went for a hug, and Matt was quickly swooped.


Matt didn't like physical contact, the different textures, sensations, smells... overwhelmed him.


Not this one thought.


This hug came as relief, for his anxiety ridden mind.

The bright lights of the party made Matt dizzy for a moment and start dissociating the next.

He left his things on a chair and went for a drink, or two.

After some time, one of the nurses noticed that Matt seemed to react negatively to the bright neon lights of the corridors and rooms. And that on the contrary to the other babies, he was rather calm when completely engulfed by darkness. So that’s what the nurses and his mom did.
They assured themselves that Matt was always in a dark room, and only turned on one of the lights when absolutely necessary.

The lights at the party reminded Matt of the story of how he was born.
His mom really liked to talk about it, and would bring it up often, even among her friends, despite Matt being uncomfortable
every time. The story went something like this: Matt’s mom had a difficult pregnancy, being bedridden for the last three months
of it.
When he was finally born, Matt came out smoothly with no screams and no agony.
Matt’s mother didn’t really feel him come out of there.
Until Matt actually came out, the room was silent.
After that, it was endless screaming and crying.
Nothing would seemed to calm him down. He wasn’t feeding nor sleeping.

After a few drinks Matt finally felt like tackling some small talk with people present at the party.


This went on for a while until one of them excused themselves and started to try and gather everyone present.
Everyone if I could please have your attention for just a minute!
Yea guys we have something important to share with you all *snorts*
The room went almost silent except for a few laughs and sarcatistic smiles.
Okay now that I have your attention, I would like to call Matt to the center of the room, as he has something he would like to share with all of us!
Yeah come on Matt! Don't let us hanging!

Matt was officially sweating, if there was something he hated even more than talking to strangers one on one, was talking to a room full of strangers, who were activately listening to him and excepting something from him.

Matt took a deep breath, took his bags of bones and went to the center of the room.

To reassure himself he looked at Kimberly all the time.

He started to take one bone out of the bag, and describing what animal it belonged to, how he obtained it, how he cleaned it etcetera.


It didn't take long before he was interruped by copious laughter coming from everyone in the room.
Damn I knew you were weird and everything but I didn't actually except you to pull THIS off! AHAHAHAHA
Yea man what the fuck, you know we were joking right? You ACTUALLY brought bones to showcase to the party? What is wrong with you? Nobody cares about this stuff except you! You freak! AHAHAHAHAHAH
Damn, you are so pathetic it's actually kinda sad lol
Yea.. what the fuck man... that's creepy. You actually go in the woods and clean random bones you find lying around? GROSS.
Damn Matt, I knew you were SPECIAL but this is a whole other level of DESPERATE and PATHETIC!
Matt started crying and hyperventilating, having nowhere to run he just went straight to the bathroom and locked the door

Matt didn't know what was worse:

The cruelty of everyone around him or the fact that EVEN Kimberly was making fun of him
Matt couldn't move, or do anything at all. He was totally paralyzed, standing in a corner of the bathroom. Thinking about what had just happened. Thinking about Kimberly.

His mind started to wander so much that he started to make up fake scenarios of an imaginary relationship with Kimberly in his mind.


They all ended the same, with the events of tonight.



His mind was on the edge of breaking when suddenly...
Hey Matt, you okay? You've been in there a while, come on out! We were just joking around!

Hearing Kimberly's voice broke Matt out of his delusion and snapped him back to reality.

He was still in shocked and his cheeks wet with tears, but he decided to come out of the bathroom.
Yeah, I'll be right out...

To appear more confident, laugh at your own jokes, like this:


AHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHHAHAHAHAHHAHAHAHAHHAHAHAHAHILARIOUS!

Matt couldn’t pick himself from the floor for several minutes, his cheeks wet with tears.
The new loop of the cassette wasn’t helping
either, making him feel like he was actually going crazy.
He couldn’t stop thinking about what happened at
the party and gaslighting himself into being more
positive, trying to not spiral, wasn’t working.


He needed to cry.

He finally managed to sit up on the floor and stared at the videocassette player one last time before getting up.
He couldn’t be bothered with that problem
right now.
It was now past 3 A.M. in the morning and Matt suddenly felt a profound sense of
restlessness, as it often happened to him late at night.
He knew that he desperately needed sleep, especially after the recent events, but couldn’t bring himself to go to bed.
He first tried to watch something on his computer but ultimately decided to play a few games of four-dimensional chess, giving up halfway when he remembered he couldn’t play chess very well.

Instead he put on some music and stared at the ceiling for two hours.
It was now 5 A.M. and the sun was coming up.
This was a clear sign for Matt that he needed to take some of his sleeping pills if he was to ever fall asleep. Matt got up from bed, set his headphones aside and went into the bathroom.
Upon coming out of the bathroom it was apparent to Matt that several hours had passed and that Kimberly was wasted.
Heyyyy Matt, how are you doing?? What were you doing in there? Uh?
Oh come oooon, don't be like this! I know you are having fun, it was just a joke! It was FUNNY! It's OKAY! Come on, let's go out!!
Matt was taken by the arm by Kimberly and taken outside, where several people were sitting on the grass, watching the moon and stars
Heyy Matt, you know what we should do? WE SHOULD DITCH THIS PARTY AND GO DANCE!
...what?
YEAH COME ON! It will be fun! Let's go dance together, just the two of us!
...How? You are clearly drunk and I don't have a car... Plus it's not like I exactly feel like it...
Actually, if anything, I should take you to one of the bedrooms and put you to bed... before you hurt yourself...
UGHH, you're such a party killer! FINE! I'll go by myself! Enjoy your boring life I guess :P
Before Matt could say anything more, Kimberly was already climbing in her car and starting the engine to God knows where.

Matt proceeded to go back into the house, as he felt he was gonna pass out from all the emotions.

He found a semi-quiet corner on one of the couches.

A cat also sat there so Matt decided to pet them, as it was useful in calming him down.
Matt started to think again about what had happened, trying to make sense of it, or at least make order in the various thought he was having.

One particularly stuck out:

Matt felt no hate towards Kimberly.

No resentment.
No bitterness.
Nothing negative, and nothing new.


It was like nothing happened.
It was like his image of her was carefully protected behind bullet proof glass.

Matt started to think that maybe he had a serious problem, and what he felt for Kimberly wasn't love nor enfatuation. But more like a disease.


Like Stockholm Syndrome.

Locate the nearest exit and leave abruptly, avoid eye contact, don't say goodbye.


No one will notice.
Exit the party
Exit your life

Matt left the party and started going back to his house, while remembering to take his bones home with him.

This caused a few laughs and snorts, but Matt ignored them.

Matt entered the bathroom of his apartment.

He reached the cabinet where he kept his pills and took one.

He then sat on the floor for a moment in search of stability.

The thoughts he was having came back like a truck.

He decided to take another pill.

And another.
And another.
And another.

Soon more than half the bottle was empty.

This is were Matt started to panic and quickly called the emergency services.

To then pass out while he was still on the phone.

This hallucination Matt was experiencing, quickly came to an end when he woke up in sweat, in his pyjamas, in an ambulance.

HEY HEY! HE IS AWAKE!

Matt, oh my god, please be okay, say something please!

Matt could only mumble some vague question, which Kimberly tried to answer to the best of her ability.

They were then separated, so that Matt could receive the care he needed.
